{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489216"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:10:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:10:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"618"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/618"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.11,0.07,0.54,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84770"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/618"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"482"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"2181"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10733"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84770"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a first-onset seizure. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She drinks two glasses of wine at weekends but does not smoke. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal a brain tumour with high-grade features and extensive vasogenic oedema on imaging. She is commenced on dexamethasone 4 mg four times daily for symptomatic relief and planned for resection in one week.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate perioperative steroid management in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current dose without supplementation","Measure morning cortisol level","Perform ACTH stimulation test","Administer perioperative stress-dose steroids","Perform insulin-tolerance test"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a brain tumour requiring high-dose dexamethasone (equivalent to \u0026gt;100mg prednisolone daily) for management of cerebral oedema. The key consideration is whether perioperative stress-dose steroids are required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current dose without supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate as the patient has been on steroids for less than three weeks. The hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis takes at least three weeks of exogenous steroid exposure to develop clinically significant suppression, regardless of dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasure morning cortisol level\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for patients on intermediate doses (5-20mg prednisolone equivalent) for more than three weeks. This patient\u0027s duration of steroid use is too short to warrant testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform ACTH stimulation test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to clarify indeterminate cases where morning cortisol levels fall between 140-275 nmol/L. It is not indicated here given the short duration of steroid use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister perioperative stress-dose steroids\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for patients taking \u0026gt;20mg prednisolone equivalent daily for more than three weeks. Despite the high dose, this patient\u0027s short duration of use means stress dosing is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform insulin-tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E is considered the gold standard for assessing HPA axis function but is not required here given the short duration of steroid use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDexamethasone is commonly used pre-operatively for brain tumours as it reduces cerebral oedema by stabilising the blood-brain barrier and decreasing vascular permeability. The duration of pre-operative steroid use is guided by the patient\u0027s clinical condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Exogenous steroids taken for less than three weeks are unlikely to cause clinically significant HPA axis suppression.","Doses of prednisolone equivalent \u003E20mg/day for greater than three weeks require perioperative stress dosing.","Dexamethasone is commonly used pre-operatively for brain tumours to reduce cerebral oedema."],"references":["Cooper MS, Stewart PM. Corticosteroid insufficiency in acutely ill patients. The New England journal of medicine. 2003;348:727-34. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/nejmra020529","Dietrich J, Rao K, Pastorino S, Kesari S. Corticosteroids in brain cancer patients: benefits and pitfalls. Expert Rev Clin Pharmacol. [Internet] 2011 Mar;4(2):233-42. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3109638/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"618"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69062"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T20:10:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T20:10:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"618"}},"content":{"data":{"ty